DMARC - Domain-based Message Authentication, Reporting & Conformance


Big companies like PayPal, Google, Microsoft, and Yahoo developed a relatively new framework called DMARC that helps domain owners prevent attackers from spoofing their domains to stop email spoofing threats. In other words, DMARC helps domain owners detect and prevent email spoofing.


The DMARC standard -Domain-based Message Authentication, Reporting & Conformance- was first published in 2012 to prevent email abuse. At that time, a small number of companies adopted it, essentially companies with expert security professionals. Recently, the adoption is growing, and many companies have implemented DMARC to secure their email system. At the moment, DMARC is the most up-to-date protection against email spoofing. 


To describe how DMARC works, lets think of it as a communication protocol you -the domain owner- utilize to provide mail servers around the world that receive emails from @your-domain.com with two critical things:

  1. Ability to detect spoofed messages. Messages that look like they came from your domain (i.e., attackers spoofing your domain in the email sender field blabla@yourdomain.com).
  2. Instructions on what actions other organizations should take upon receiving a spoofed message from your domain (i.e., reject the mail or receive it but place it in the spam folder).

In the last exercise, we noticed that when we spoofed amazon.com, we received the email in our Gmail inbox. However, we did not receive the message when we tried the same with Microsoft.com. This is a clear example of how Microsoft used DMARC to allow the receiving mail server -Gmail server, in that case - to detect and reject @microsoft.com spoofed emails.


Figure - zoom in


Phishing is an ongoing and annoying problem for Microsoft. In fact, microsoft.com is the most spoofed domain online. Unsurprisingly, Microsoft enforced an aggressive DMARC policy to drop spoofed messages. To understand how DMARC works, we have first to explain two other protocols/components DMARC protocol depends on; SPF and DKIM.
